		<br>
		</td></tr></table>
	<!-- Postbit User Info -->
</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 08-03-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">11:44 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">A cold wind blows through the trees scattering the last of autum's golden leaves arcoss the clearing. Huddled around a small fire sits an odd asortment of adventures; a holy knight of Tunare lounges on a fallen log sharpening his sword, a dwarven priest prepares the nights meal,  a darkelf wizard sets wards around the camp, A woodelf... warrior (Wait a second, Wood Elves can be warriors?!... Yes, now shut up and let me tell the story.), two more woodelves, a druid and a ranger, are cleaning a brace of rabbits. The dwarf looks at the pair and says, "Briscoe, Greystone if you two don't hurry up with those rabbits the bread will burn." Greystone, laying his scimitar down, looks at the dwarf and says, "Nyvn the bread is always brunt." Briscoe silenty rolls his eyes and looks over at the paladin. He says, "Sinestil, there they go again." Sinestil says,"They're worse than old housewives." Nyvn grabs a loaf of dark bread and hurls it at Sinestil. The loaf makes a solid sounding clank sound on Sinestil's armor. Off to the side a snore escapes from the warrior. Greystone exclaims, "Look at Brelwan there sleeping through all the commotion." Brelwans opens an eye, looks around, and promtly closes it again.<br />
<br />
Affairs around the camp have settled down a bit, and I find myself wondering, "What on earth could possibly convinced me to leave the comfort of Kaladim ( well the bars of Kaladim) and go traveling off to the frigid wastes of Velious?" The smell of burning bread brings me back to reality. "Foods done," I say. My party gathers around the small fire, and we help ourselves to the food. "Anyone else want some tea?" I ask. Greystone laughs, and says, "Tea! Hah, Hah I say, that stuff has enough alcohol to clean armor! We don't even need tender to start the fire, just pour a little bit on the wood and it burts into flame." "Are you still mad about last night? Honestly how was I to know one small cup would get you THAT drunk... And you certainly cann't blame me for you wandering off in the woods and falling in the stream," I reply to him. He glowers at me, but shuts up. We set into the food and all was quite until Briscoe spoke up and said, "Hmp this bread is burnt just like always." I sweetly say to him, "You can always eat that fruit you always forage up. I mean you don't have to leave it laying around all over the place." The meal finishes without further incident and I bank the fire for the night. I roll up in my blankets and promptly fall alseep. I awake to a chill morning thats well below freezing. All the while thinking to my self that a nice bar stool in Kaladim would be far more comfortable. We break out some rations and get ready for the days march. We head across the commons for the tunnel to the Desert of Ro. We reach it around mid-day and decide to take a short break. I decide to look around for something interesting. Sadly I can only afford a Small Wisdom Diety, better than nothing I say to myself. After equiping what can only be termed a doll. I head back to the others. "About time," mutters Greystone. Sinestil piques up with, "Nice doll there Nyvn." I smile good-naturedly at their jests. We pass out of the tunnels darkenss and walk into blinding sunlight. I squint and ask, "How long do we have to stay in this?" Brelwan answers, "Less if we don't waste time talking." I shake my head in wonder at him. As if he wasn't the bigest chatter box after having some of my Tea. After what seems like forever we reach a small dock. On the dock is one of the craziest things I've ever seen... A Gnome pretending to be a Pirate. I board the waiting boat with some trepidation. The whole thing seems to be held together entirely by some rather ratty looking ropes. I drop my pack and sink eagerly after it. Greystone, as usual is goofing around. He's postering and looking at his reflection in the water. Sinestil sneaks up behind him and gives him a small shove. Greystone goes flying out over the water, and lands with a huge splash. He indignatly shouts, " That wasn't funny!" Sinestil says, "That should help the smell a little bit." Greystone, even angrier, shouts, "I do not stink!" Sinestil grins. I do my best to keep a straight face, but it's a loosing battle. After a few seconds of stuggle I burst out laughing. Greystone sniffs and tries to climb onto the boat. After watching him struggle Brelwans walks over and pulls him out.  Greystone, looking like a drowned rat plops down in a corner and refuses to speak to anyone. We all get settled in and the pirate, I still cann't get over a gnomish pirate, unties the rickety contraption. I join Garrath in the prow of the ship and he says, "I cann't belive that tommorw we'll be in Velious. It seems unreal, until a few short months ago most of the world didn't even know the place existed." He returns to silently gazing out at the growing number of iceburgs. We settle in for yet another evening meal, this one cold. We still have left overs from last nights meal; so I break them out and pass the around. Greystone mutter something about how if he has any teeth left after this he'll cound himself lucky. I ignore him and after our meal we all get somesleep.<br />
<br />
 I awake to a burning cold, and looking around I see the sunriseing over the lost continent of Velious. It's a sight that is breathtakingly beautiful, and left me at a loss for words. We are all awestruck at the sight of this deadly place we've all heard so much about. All of us except Greystone who's still snoring in his blankets. Brelwan goes over and nudges Greystone with his foot. Greystone sits straight up and  sighs like a heart broken man. Garrath wispers, "I'd wager I know who he was dreaming about." I nod and reply in a low voice, "Hmp, the fool, she's over 3 times his age, and stuffy high elf to boot." Garrath sighs and mumbles something about the follies of youth. Shortly we make land fall at a dock manned by more of the gnomish "pirates". A paticulaly short one over in the corner keeps sneaking glances at a small book. While Brelwan and Briscoe are confering about our path I take a look around the shops and realize what a good thing it was we brought our provisions with us, their prices are insane. Brelwan calls me back to the group and we take off. Shortly I learned to hate walking through the snow, even with Brelwan and Brisco breaking the trail ahead of me it's very heavy going. Suddenly Greystone screams, much like a small girl does when you drop a spider in her dress... not that I'd know what that sounds like. I turn around to see a strange creature made entirly of whirling debreis attacking him. Briscoe fires off an arrow, but it flies harmlessly through the creature. I pray the Brell to heal our wayward druid with his power, and Garrath blasts the creature into small fragments with a quick spell. Suddenly a chill runs down my spine and I very much long for my familar bar stool. We get Greystone settled down with a little bit of my Tea, only a little bit mind you, and resume our trek. On the horizen a black finger starts to grow larger and larger, casting an ominous shadow acorss the snow. We aproach a small set of huts in the shadow cast by the massive tower. Strange white gnolls walk about between them. We set in a circle a short distance from them. Brelwan explains that this is the Tower of Frozen Shadow, a paticularly apt name in my opinion. He continues that the tower is reported to be full of undead. I'm immediatly focused, I ache in every fiber of my being to wipe the Norrath clean of undead corruption. Settling in for a camp with no fire we slip into the sleep of the truely tired. In the morning we make a dash for the towe and quickly regroup inside. Greystone breaks the eriey silence by saying, "This places doesn't feel right." Sinestil speaks up and says, "It's a haunted tower, what do you expect... it to feel like Gfay?" Greystone responds, "Fine ignore me, but don't say I didn't warn you. This place is bad news." We slowly start walking into the depths of the tower when suddenly Garrath starts to slip. Before we can react he falls into a dark abys, his scream echoing long after he's gone. I look down the hole, but only darkness awaits. I call out his name, but only my own twisted echo's can be heard mocking my attemps to revive Garrath. Greystone with a sullen look on his face says, "I told you guys this place was ill omened." Brelwan with command snapping in his voice tells Greystone, "Shut up, we all knew the dangers  of embarking on an adventure like this. He accepted that he might not go home. If the danger is too much for you the ship isn't far." Greystone glanced around, but finding no support did exactly that and shut up. We proceed deeper into the bowels of this acursed tower, when suddenly out of the silent shadows a seeming horde of undead falls upon us. Greystone manages to root a few before they reach us, but still seven of the accursed creatures reach us. Greystone blasts one into tiny bone fragments, as Sinestil and Brelwan each are assaulted by two ghosts. The other three speed after Greystone, and strike at him. Gashing his face open. He reels in pain, but within seconds my healing spells make his wounds nearly disapear. To late I realize my mistanke as the creatures turn to attack me. I block several clumsy stickes with my sheild and smash ones head in. Greystone quickly recoves and destroys the other two on me. I turn my attention back to our melee in time to watch Brelwan preform a coup dé grace on an one armed skeleton. Sinestil with a huge grin splitting his face exclaims that he wants more. Just as he speaks the two that Greystone rooted break free and attack him. He skillfully slays one, but the other gets a lucky strike through his armor stabbing under his arm, and into his rib cage. Brelwan silently attack the remaining creature as Sinestil, whiter than normal collapses to the ground. I force my self out fo the shock I was in and quickly cast the strongest heal that I know. Sine's face return to it's normal pasty shade and he strans up straight. Brelwan shows us the weapon the creature had been weilding, a dagger with a strange enchantment upon it. It looked to my untrained eye like it would summon bandages for the weilder. Brelwan and Sine pull out the dice and roll for the strange item. Brelwan, as usualy, has shitty luck loosing the roll by a large margin. Sine sits for a moment admiring his new dagger before slipping it in his belt. We cautiously restart our treck into the dark regions of the tower. We asscend to the second floor and Greystone exclaims, "It's a library!" He rushes to one of the nearby bookcases, when suddenly a large spike explodes up from the floor impaling Greystone through his entire body. I'm to stunded to even try to save him, and all I can do is watch as the life drains out of his usually cheerful eyes. In a state of shock all I can do is mutter no over and over. Brelwan grabs me by the shoulders and shakes me yelling at me to get a grip. I can barely hear him, and care even less. Suddenly my ears are ringing and my cheak smarts. His slap managed to brek me out of my misery. We lay Greystone's body out with his weapon at his side. Try as we might we cann't wipe the look of utter agaony off his face. We confer and decide that we're not turning back after all that we've been through and press on. The journey through the empty library is uneventful, aside from the trap that is. We battle our way through afloor after floor of scattered undead. We reach the entrance to the sixth floor and decide to make our camp there. We eat a meal of hard rations and water and quickly roll for our watches.Of course I get the middle watch. I lay down and close my eyes. It seemed only moments later Brelwan was shaking me awake. "Hey, It's your watch. he wispers" "Already? I ask in a sleeply stupor. He looks at me as if I've lost my mind, and goes to his blankets and is promtly fast asleep. I stand up and sit watching into the darkness. The silence is so deep my ears ring from straining to hear anything. After a while I hear something. Try as I might I hear only silence when I attempt to identify where the sound came from. After what seemed an eternity of waiting in the dark I hear it again. Closer this time, I can tell what it is. A woman weeping, it takes me a moment to realize that the sound is growing louder. Sudden;y out fo the dark comes a glowing apparition. An etherially beatiful woman floats abaove the ground weeping, endlessly weeping. I ask her name, but suddenly she's no longer there. The rest of my watch passes without event, and I wake Sinestil from his sleep. "Your turn now bro." He silently nodds and gets out of his blankets. I wrap back in my blanckets but it's hours until I finnaly drift off to dreams of the weeping woman. I'm shaken unrested from my blankets for the days march. we assend to the next floor and it fight a new type of creature large golems, They're firce and difficult to kill, but we manage with only minor wounds to travel deep into the levels interior. We turn a corner and run into a large gathering of undead. They seem to be gathered for a weeding cerimony, but the quickly fall upon us. It's all I can do to keep the three of us alive. I'm quickly running out of mana and Brelwan and Sinestil's attacks are growing slower and slower. A mountain of undead are piling up, but their numbers seem limitless. Sinestil falls, his helm split in half. Brelwan yells out for vengance and his attacks gain new fury. We fight on and the undead's numbers seem to be lessening. I'm gorwing wearing, never have I healed so much in such a short time. We fight our way to the head of the cerimony. Brelwan falls to the floor, and my heal barely catches him in time. He bounces back into the fight. He says over his shoulder, "Dwarf this is no time for games!" I grin weakly and continue smashing undead and casting my heals. One of the undead attacks me from behind breaking my concentration. My spell is interupted and Brelwan falls to the floor in a growing pool of blood. Suddenly I'm no longer under attack. It takes a moment for me to realize that I''ve reached the head of the wedding. the ghostly bride turns around. I gasp in shock, the woman from last night! She smiles at me, but it only affects her lips. Cold starts to spread up my limbs and into my body, everything is going black. I start to swoon, but before I hit the floor everythign has gone black and I no longer feel the biting cold that has affected me since I landed on this acursed content.</font></p>
	
